  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Monday Morg</p>
      <p>Dearest Old Crow. Thanks for your long letter! I am improving, and getting in all things happier &amp; more settled.</p>
      <p>I have little to say, for I live so very quietly, seeing scarcely any one; &amp; find increasingly</p>
      <p>that my home-studies, (be they in turn, music, science, or literature, are what best suit me. The Theatres I get to love merely as instruments of study [double underline too; going now with my packet of music generally; to the quietest back-seat I can get, &amp; feeling absorbed in the artistical ideas suggested by the performance!-- I enjoy</p>
      <p>London as conducing to all this cultivation; but the Thrush likes too to hear what happens in the fair &amp; beautiful country, which after all is God's own work, far more than all Towns!</p>
      <p>Dear William! I find I enjoy pictures much of late; &amp; perhaps you (who in this are so good a judge &amp; critique), will help to develop my taste &amp; knowledge in this line!</p>
      <p>Oh! You'll see I shall become a very artistical Avis, in all things;-- and all the better for having Science as a foundation, &amp; the imaginative &amp; creative developped only after [very thick underline] "la "premiere [accent mark over the 2nd "e"] jeunesse"!--</p>
      <p>[next three lines of text completely crossed out]</p>
      <p>So believe me, my Dear. Thine ever engaging,-- Thy fairest and gentlest of thrushes!</p>
    </div></body>
